\doublespace\large{
\chapter{\\FACTORS INFLUENCING RETROTRANSPOSON DISTRIBUTION IN GENES}

Retrotransposons comprise approximately half of the human genome and contribute to chromatin structure, regulatory motifs, and protein-coding sequences. Since retrotransposon insertions can disrupt functional genetic elements as well as introduce new sequence motifs to a region, they have the potential to affect the function of genes that harbor insertions as well as those nearby. Partly as a result of these effects, the distribution of retrotransposons across the genome is non-uniform and there are observed imbalances in the orientation of insertions with respect to the transcriptional direction of the containing gene. Although some of the factors underlying the observed distributions are understood, much of the variability remains unexplained. Detailed characterization of retrotransposon density in genes could help inform predictions of the functional consequence of \textit{de novo} as well as polymorphic insertions. In order to characterize the relationship between genes and inserted elements, it is important to examine the distribution of retrotransposons and their internal motifs within tissue-specific and housekeeping genes. 


%ASbias (Linear Decay)
\section{The Current Distribution of Alu and L1 within Genes}
    
%Linear Decay
\subsection{L1 and Alu Antisense bias exhibits a linear decay across gene deciles}
\label{sec:as_dec}
The dependency of AS bias on position within a gene was calculated for both Alu and L1, where position was defined as one of ten deciles of a gene. RefSeq genes were divided into these deciles using the boundaries of transcription start (TSS) and transcription stop, including introns (figure \ref{fig:decile}). Previous research had used distance from the TSS to examine RT density, this alternative approach of normalizating genes by length expanded the scope of the analysis to examine the effect of relative position on RT density, and therefore the ability to detect any regions of the gene that are more sensitive to RT insertions. A side-effect of normalizing by the TSS and transcription stop positions was that every decile 1 (first decile) and decile 10 (last decile) contained an exon. Since deciles 2 - 9 (internal deciles) were not defined by any discrete exon boundary, they were variable as to the presence of an exon. Although the first and last deciles inevitably contained an exon, it was not necessarily a coding exon (ie: 5\rq-UTR or 3\rq-UTR). AS and S RTs (L1 or Alu) were counted within each decile and normalized by the total number of (AS + S) RTs in all deciles.\\

    %Figure Decile Explanation
    \begin{figure}[!ht]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth,natwidth=610,natheight=642]{decile.png}
    \caption{\textbf{Normalizing Genes by Length\\} Example of a gene broken up into deciles. Decile 1 contains the first 0-10\% of the gene, and decile 10 contains the last 90-100\% of the gene. Deciles were calculated from transcription start to transcription stop site from the RefSeq annotated genes.}
    \label{fig:decile}
    \end{figure}
    
\subsubsection{Alu}
AS and S Alu were counted in each decile and normalized by the total number of Alu within all deciles (figure \ref{fig:lineardecay_alu}). As expected due to the known AS-bias, there were more AS Alu than S Alu overall within RefSeq genes. Alu in the S orientation were distributed relatively equally across the internal deciles with drops in density occuring only in the first and last deciles that contain the UTRs. Conversely, AS Alu exhibited a linear decay in distribution with the highest point at decile 2 and the lowest point at decile 10. Similarly to Alu on the S strand, AS Alu also showed decreased in density, outside of the linear decrease, in the first and last deciles. The high level of AS Alu in the second decile mimicks previous studies that have shown an increase in Alu near the TSS. Interestingly, though, there is a steady decline in AS Alu that is highly dependent on the normalized gene decile within which the Alu resides.
        
    %Figure Linear Decay: Alu
    \begin{figure}[!h]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth,natwidth=610,natheight=642]{lineardecay_alu.pdf}
    \caption{\textbf{AS bias of Alu decays linearly across gene boundaries\\}Counts of Alu in the AS and S orientation per decile were normalized by the total Alu in all RefSeq genes. as = antisense, s = sense}
    \label{fig:lineardecay_alu}
    \end{figure}
    
\subsubsection{L1}     
AS L1 showed very similar density distributions within genes that Alu did. There was an overall increase in AS L1 compared to S L1, S L1 remained relatively constant throughout all gene deciles, and AS L1 exhibited a linear decile across deciles 2 - 10 (figure \ref{fig:lineardecay_l1}). There were also some differences between the pattern observed with L1 and the pattern observed with Alu. As is echoed in the overall AS-bias, there was a larger difference between AS L1 and S L1 within each decile, than that which is observed in Alu. This is further emphasized by the S and AS elements having reached a point of equal density in the last inner decile for Alu, while AS L1 remain more prevalent than S in every decile. \\
    
    %Figure Linear Decay: L1
    \begin{figure}[!h]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth,natwidth=610,natheight=642]{lineardecay_l1.pdf}
    \caption{\textbf{AS bias of L1 decays linearly across gene boundaries\\}Counts of L1 in the AS and S orientation per decile were normalized by the total L1 in all RefSeq genes. as = antisense, s = sense}
    \end{figure}
   

\newpage Both AS L1 and Alu began at a relatively high frequency in decile 2 and declined until decile 10. To determine the rate of AS decay across gene deciles, analysis was restricted to the internal deciles. This avoided the confounding effects from the process of normalization. Slopes were calculated with the counts of raw elements as opposed to the proportions to facilitate interpretation (table \ref{table:lindecay}). As expected, the decile number had a significant impact on AS density in both Alu and L1, with Alu reduced by -994 elements per decile and L1 by -1410 elements per decile. S elements were not significantly effected by the decile within which they resided.\\

    
    % Table Slope of Linear Decay
    % Thu Apr 10 13:47:08 2014
   \begin{table}[ht]
   \centering
   \begin{tabular}{rllrrr}
     \hline
    & Element & Orientation & Estimate & p(intercept) & p(decile) \\ 
    \hline
  1 & Alu & AS & -1410.67 & 7.45e-12 & 5.53e-08 \\ 
    2 & Alu & S & -27.17 & 2.33e-10 & 6.08e-01 \\ 
    3 & L1 & AS & -993.60 & 2.40e-08 & 2.00e-04 \\ 
    4 & L1 & S & 32.88 & 3.09e-07 & 6.91e-01 \\ 
