%AS bias (distribution near 5'-UTR)
\section{Gene-specific variables associated with RT distribution}

The fact that RTs undergo differential selective pressures depending on the orientation of element with respect to a gene is intriguing. It indicates that there must be some effect of the RT insertion on the phenotype of the organism that is dependent both on the insertion event, and also on the sequence of the RT. If RTs do indeed have specific effects on genes depending on the sequence of the RT then new insertions should be able to be classified as to the potential effect on the gene and potentially the phenotype. This is especially important for disease studies, where it is imperitive to have as much information as possible on a new variation to filter out false positives from the true source of phenotypic variation. The differential purifying selection between AS and S RTs indicates that this sequence-specific interaction between RT and gene, may indeed be true. When asking what is causing RTs within genes to undergo purifying selection there are two classes of variables to examine; variables associated with genes (eg: 5\rq-UTR density, coding sequence density), and variables associated with RTs (eg: length of the RT, sequence motifs contained with the RT).    

%Correlation of Linear Decay with 5'-UTR
\subsection{Alu and L1 are Decreased Near 5\rq-UTR}

Previous studies using raw distances in base pairs have shown that RTs are increased near TSSs. Interestingly in the analysis using normalized distances the AS bias was increased near the TSS, but at a ratio that was less than what would be expected based on the linear trend from the internal deciles. As mentioned earlier, the first decile was defined by the TSS and was therefore enriched for the presence of  5\rq-UTRs (figure \ref{fig:utr_nosecond}), however the presence of a coding exon was not obligatory by the normalization procedure (figure \ref{cds_noUTR}). It was therefore possible that normalizing by the TSS exaggerated an effect of the UTR on RT density. It was therefore important to first study if AS RT density near the TSS was correlated with the presence of the 5\rq-UTR or was due to another latent variable. To accomplish this, the effect of the 5\rq-UTR had to be seperated from any latent effects correlated with the first decile. To seperate out these effects, genes were identified that contained a second 5\rq-UTR within deciles other than the first decile. These 2$^\circ$ 5\rq-UTRs are commonly due to either alternative start positions of transcription, or transcription of a seperate gene that begins within the boundaries of another gene. Examples of genes that contained secondary 5\rq-UTRs are depicted in figure \ref{fig:25utr}. 


    %Figure 5'-UTR in genes with no internal 5'-UTR
    \begin{figure}[!ht]
        \centering
        \includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth,natwidth=610,natheight=642]{utr_nosecond.pdf}
        \caption{\textbf{Distribution of 5\rq-UTRs in genes with no 2$^\circ$ 5\rq-UTRs\\}Proportion of 5\rq-UTRs were calculated for each gene decile for genes lacking a second 5\rq-UTR within the gene boundaries.}
        \label{fig:utr_nosecond}
    \end{figure}
    

    %Figure 5'-UTR examples
    \begin{figure}[!ht]
        \centering
        \includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth,natwidth=610,natheight=642]{25utr.png}
        \caption{\textbf{Examples of Genes Containing Secondary 5'-UTRs:\\} RAB42, GLB3, and CLCNKB are examples of genes with alternative 5'-UTRs within the gene boundaries. RAB42 contains the secondary 5'-UTR in the 10 - 20\% bin, GLB3 in the 20 - 30\% bin, and CLCNKB in the 30-40\% bin. Orange: Gene classified as containing the primary UTR; Green: Gene classified as containing the secondary UTR.}
        \label{fig:25utr}
    \end{figure}
    

Once genes with internal 5\rq-UTRs were identified, they were further grouped into subsets based on the decile location of the 2$^\circ$ 5\rq-UTRs. For example, Group I genes contained all 2$^\circ$ 5\rq-UTRs in the first decile, calculated as the first 0\% - 10\% of the gene. Group II contained genes where the 2$^\circ$ 5\rq-UTRs was in the second decile (10\% - 20\% of the gene), and so on for all ten deciles (figure \ref{fig:5utr_diag}). The frequencies of all AS and S L1 and Alu were then calculated within these gene groups and compared to expectation based on genes lacking any 2$^\circ$ 5\rq-UTRs. 

    
    %Figure 5'-UTR Analysis
    \begin{figure}[!h]
        \centering
        \includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth,natwidth=610,natheight=642]{5utr_diag.pdf}
        \caption{\textbf{Design for analyzing the impact of internal 5\rq-UTRs on RT density\\}Light green: Genes with only one 5'-UTR located between the transcription start (TSS) and transcription stop site. Dark green: Genes with a second 5\rq-UTR between TSS and transcription stop. Red bar: Decile containing the second 5\rq-UTR. The UTR in the 5\rq-most position was defined as the primary (1$^\circ$) 5\rq-UTR. Dark green genes were grouped by the decile (bin) containing the secondary (2$^\circ$) UTR. All groups were then normalized by the secondary 5\rq-UTR position by defining the bin that contained the 2$^\circ$ UTR as 0. Each bin downstream was defined consecutively as 1, 2, ... 7, and each bin upstream was defined as -1, -2,...-7.}
        \label{fig:5utr_diag}
    \end{figure}


    
    %Figure 5'-UTR in genes with secondary 5'UTRs
    \begin{figure}[!ht]
        \centering
        \includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth,natwidth=610,natheight=642]{utr_second.pdf}
        \caption{\textbf{Distribution of 5\rq-UTRs in genes containing 2$^\circ$ 5\rq-UTRs\\}Proportion of 2$^\circ$ 5\rq-UTRs were calculated after normalization as described in figure \ref{fig:5utr_diag}. Decile 0 is the decile containing the 2$^\circ$ 5\rq-UTR. All negative deciles are upstream of the 2$^\circ$ 5\rq-UTR, and all positive deciles are downstream.}
        \label{fig:utr_second}
    \end{figure}
    


\hspace{-15pt}\textit{Alu} \\AS Alu in genes containing 2$^\circ$ UTRs were similar in density to the AS Alu in genes lacking 2$^\circ$ UTRs (figure \ref{fig:2utr_ASalu}). The normalized, 0, decile containing the 2$^\circ$ UTR (mean: 0.049) was significantly reduced compared to the same decile in genes without 2$^\circ$ UTRs (mean: 0.058) (Student's t-test p < 0.039). S Alu showed a slight trend towards an increase over expectation upstream of the 0 decile (figure \ref{fig:2utr_Salu}). The 0 decile, however, was significantly decreased beyond expectation (mean second UTR: 0.41 ; mean no second UTR: 0.46 ; Student's t-test p < 5.2e-04) similar to the AS Alu. 

    %Figure 5'-UTR AS Alu
    \begin{figure}[!ht]
        \centering
        \includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth,natwidth=610,natheight=642]{2utr_ASalu.pdf}
        \caption{\textbf{Change in AS Alu density in the presence of a 2$^\circ$ 5\rq-UTR\\}Proportion of 2$^\circ$ AS Alu proportions were calculated as described in figure \ref{fig:5utr_diag}. All proportions were normalized by the expected proportion based on RefSeq genes that have no 2$^\circ$ within the gene boundaries. }
        \label{fig:2utr_ASalu}
    \end{figure}
    
    
    
    %Figure 5'-UTR S Alu
    \begin{figure}[!ht]
        \centering
        \includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth,natwidth=610,natheight=642]{2utr_Salu.pdf}
        \caption{\textbf{Change in S Alu density in the presence of a secondary 5\rq-UTR\\}Calculated similarly to figure \ref{fig:2utr_ASalu}}
        \label{fig:2utr_Salu}
    \end{figure}
    
    
\hspace{-15pt}\textit{\\L1} \\The distribution of AS L1 within genes containing 2$^\circ$ 5\rq-UTR was somewhat similar to that observed with AS Alu (figure \ref{fig:2utr_ASl1}). Interestingly, there was a slight decrease in L1 density upstream of the 0 decile for AS L1 in genes containing a 2$^\circ$ 5\rq-UTR, though this decrease was not signficant. The 0 decile was significantly reduced over expectation (mean second UTR: 0.057 ; mean no second UTR: 0.071 ; Student's t-test p < 0.007), although the S L1 were not significantly reduced (p = 0.47) (figure \ref{fig:2utr_Sl1}). These results indicated that there may be a decrease of L1 and Alu in the presence of a 5\rq-UTR, however another explanation could be that there was another latent variable associated with the 5\rq-UTR which is still be picked up in this analysis. 
    
