%Correlation of Linear Decay with CDS Exon Density
\subsection{Linear decay of AS bias is associated with coding sequence density}
Since previous studies have shown that AS RT density was inversely correlated with exon density, we next calculated the frequency of coding exons (CDS) within each decile. Indeed, CDS density increased at a linear rate across gene deciles (figure \ref{fig:cds_noUTR}). The first decile of genes contained more CDS than the second decile. This was likely due to using the TSS as a starting point for calculation, which would enrich for 5\rq-UTRs and consequently the coding exons that may be associated with them. Therefore, as has been indicated previously [9], ASO-RTs were inversely correlated with exon density (Pearson\rq s Corr. value: -0.94; p-value: 5.21e-05) (table 3). Moreover, the distributions of exons and RTs were found to be linearly increasing and decreasing across a gene, respectively, indicating a predictable pattern of RT density within gene bounds.  
    
    %Figure CDS (no secondary 5'-UTR)
    \begin{figure}[!ht]
        \centering
        \includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth,natwidth=610,natheight=642]{cds_noUTR.pdf}
        \caption{\textbf{Distribution of Coding Sequence Exons in RefSeq Genes\\}The number of coding sequence exons (CDS) in the sense orientation were normalized by all sense oriented CDS in RefSeq genes.}
        \label{fig:cds_noUTR}
    \end{figure}
    
    
%Alternative Splicing
%\textnormal\large\textit{\\\textnormal{3.2.3 } Coding Potential of the Gene Effects AS bias\\}
%Alu and L1 have often been cited as having the potential to contribute to alternative isoforms of a gene. Both Alu and L1 contain splice donor and acceptor sites and therefore can alter splice signals. Moreover, L1, and in some cases Alu, can cause premature adenylation through the polyadenylation signals located within the sequence. For these reasons, it was important to examine the linear decay of Alu and L1 in genes that are alternatively spliced.
